Because I don't think the function of leadership is to make all the decisions, conceive all the strategies for others to execute, or tell everyone what to build. It's to establish a direction, organize and energize people around it, and then let them fucking get to work.

Once you realize that not only are you in a situation where your leaders won't let you do your job, but that you yourself are becoming a leader who won't let others do their job, it's probably time to think about going somewhere else.
Before you know it you're incentivized through praise and bonuses to keep the feature train moving, and then you're exactly the kind of leader you didn't want to be.
But the joke is that they just keep coming. And the irony is that soon, you start enjoying the positive feedback on those shiny new features.

So you think, gosh, this is harder than I thought. But Rome wasn't built in a day. Let's just get past these couple of things the CEO is asking for and once we get on the other side of that, let's see if we can start building a case to change how we work.

And then you get there and you find that the person you felt was prioritizing outputs over outcomes -- that person was dealing with the same challenges you were. They were also an order taker, getting requirements handed to them -- just with more pressure and visibility.

And I think a lot of us, as we move up in ranks, believe we won't be the next generation of leaders who create feature factories in product development. We want to believe that we will be the ones who change *how* we do things around here. Who finally empower our teams.

But if we're lower down in the hierarchy, what do we think our leaders should be doing? Well, probably some variation of "tell me where we're headed, give me some guidance and guardrails, and then get out of the way."

Consider top-down product development. At the heart of this frustration is a conflict of leadership purpose: those at the top of a hierarchy believe their purpose is to  decide what to build. After all, they have the bird's eye view. Don't they know best?
I realized that I think a lot of our challenges come from differing perspectives on what a leader is for. Beware, thread's a little rambly.

Let me tell you some numbers that I think about more often than whether I could make an even more obscene amount of money.

(FYI, 10 years tech experience, 5 in product, MBA, product leadership experience but IC right now. $165k, 15% bonus, 4.5% 401k match. I love you all so please don't come for me when it's time to burn shit down. We're hiring)
I take home a great salary. I've worked hard but not as hard as Black women in my same role for my same years of experience, for example. That's the pay disparity I'm more concerned with.

I am seeing lots of stats on pay disparity and lots of salaries flying around on this site and while these things are very important to talk about and affect marginalized women disproportionately, it misses a lot.

At this point we all should know this. We all should be painfully aware of the dismal representation of women of color, trans women, and the intersection thereof on our pedestal-ahem, I mean in our industry

Make no mistake, I (like all cis white women in tech) have been used as a distraction by companies who want to use me and people like me as their diversity yardstick to show they're 'good' and they 'value diversity'.

So, I find this day complicated. Because I am a woman and I love women and I want to celebrate us every single day. But as a white cis woman in tech, I am not as special as pink marketing wants you to believe.

Sometimes, he has to tell me about something scary he stumbled on "accidentally" on YouTube -- naming it to take its power away. And what can I do? Insist it's not real, that's all.

Every night for bed, he wants to be tucked in, have a sleep story turned on, have his light set just so, and be checked on once before he can go to sleep. He feels alone and unsafe if he's the only one awake.

My kid has a tough time sleeping. He's a digital native and is glued to the screen at every turn. He's also anxious and ADHD, like both his parents. All of this makes bedtime tough for him. We often depend on melatonin to help him.

Maybe this is obvious and didn't need a thread, but it was important to me.
Capitalism as it exists currently is violence. Having a job is self-defense. Having a job that allows you to rest, save, help others, and enjoy the one life you have is defiance.
(note -- I said smaller share, not no blame. Especially if you're white! We benefit from and are complicit in white supremacy)
relative to the folks hoarding wealth, the folks whose work is entirely aimed at protecting their position and further enriching themselves and their friends.
But ultimately, I think that on the scale of complicity, those who have to work to live bear the smallest share of the blame for this system's bloodthirst...

So I felt complicit and guilty for participating. I.e. having a job that pays me well, helps keep my family comfortable. (I also know that capitalism and white supremacy are deeply entangled, and I know I am complicit in many ways that I may not even be aware of yet.)

I don't like that the wealthy have such outsized power over the lives and health of billions of other humans and other living things on this one planet we have, the home and birthright that belongs to ALL of us.

I don't like that money makes money. I don't like that money is required for safety. I don't like that the richest people are that way because of generational and largely automated wealth, detached from work, while the demands of labor grind away at so many.
My detachment and resentment toward my current practice (product management, but this can apply to any discipline) had a lot of root in feeling complicit in the violent machine of capitalism.
I want to tell you about a reframing that's been important for my mental health and directing energy where it belongs.

@bandanjot @Yash7kumar1 If you have good resources for some of these things, I’m sure others would welcome them. I’m familiar with these concepts at this point but I was just acknowledging that it took me time to build.

A common theme: try to establish relationships *before* you need help. If you make a connection based on a transaction, chances are it won't persist once that transaction is over. Build relationships based on long-term, mutual value.
If you have one, ask a mentor/coach for a similar their experience, or what they would do if they were in the situation.

Someone who has been through something similar in another company. Often I can find war stories in blog posts and podcasts that help spark creativity and problem-solving. Sometimes I'll ask directly in a community like this and swap ideas real time.
Your dev lead and design lead are your partners and collaborators, and you can actually build a lot of goodwill and mutual confidence by asking for their advice and opinions and taking them to heart.
Build a channel with another PM on your team who is familiar with the business (if you have such a luxury) and don't be shy about asking for advice.

Your boss is an easy one, but I actually approach this one carefully and after establishing trust in the relationship. This is not how it should be, but just protective instinct built up over experience.

Three reads that have helped me have a better life with better boundaries:

Change Anything: The New Science of Personal Success (motivation/ability)
Atomic Habits by James Clear ("start small")
How to Do Nothing by Jenny Odell (you're a human being, not a human being productive)

Find something that gives you a reason to want to put work away. A book club, a pottery class, a puzzle, who the F cares. Something that you look forward to that will make it much easier mentally for you to clock out. (Structural motivation)
Tell others you are trying to set some boundaries and create some work-life balance. People understand this now and might even help you. (Social motivation)
For my fellow anxiety-havers, don't beat yourself up for checking on work after hours! If that's what you need to keep your evenings and weekends stress-free, THAT is a self care tool.

If you can't draw a tight boundary line at the end of the day, or you can't right away, at least set yourself some rules. Maybe you allow yourself to check chat/email but save all other work until the next day. (Structural ability)

Tell your boss that you need more work/life balance: "I really enjoy this job, but I need to spend more time resting and re-energizing to be at a hundred percent. Can we talk about some strategies for that?" (Social ability) (IMPORTANT: trust is a prerequisite here.)

Practice saying "no" or "later" on low-risk people before setting firmer boundaries with others. Ex. if marketing needs help with some collateral and you have a good relationship, it's easier to say "Can I help you with that next week? I'm underwater with XYZ". (Social ability)

If it's too late and you've already set those expectations, don't fret. Start small -- maybe start taking a lunch if you're not doing that. If you can't do that, how long can you take? Can you step away for a 10-minute walk? (Personal ability)

Next time you start a new job, think of your effort as a budget. Don't blow it all at the beginning and set the expectation for your performance forever. Start with maybe 60-70 percent so that when a big "expense" comes, you don't overdraft. (Personal ability)

First, something has to be amiss, and you actually have to want to do something about it. (Personal motivation) If you're working 60+ hours per week but actually having a lot of fun with no desire to change... well, you belong in a museum. 😉

I feel like there is a lot more depth to plumb here, and I'm interested in what others might recommend. Feel free to reply and take note if you are or want to be a product leader.
That said, do not act like something won't work just because you haven't seen it work.

Be candid and realistic about what changes are possible and on what time scale. If you are overly optimistic about the likelihood of success in making a change, the disappointment if it fails will be more discouraging.

Sometimes it can ease frustration to understand why things are the way they are. Teach your team about the business context to build their strategy & empathy muscles. Bonus is they can use this information to begin identifying opportunities on their own.

Know your team members' skills and goals, plan for them, and never miss an opportunity to sponsor them. This way, even if your team members are frustrated with the environment, they are still getting something out of their tenure there and might stick around longer.

When your team has bandwidth, in addition to giving them space and assigning deep work, consider loaning them out. This will build good faith and relationships with other functional teams, build their knowledge of the business, and will better position them to be more strategic.
The key to the above is using existing influence and latitude. There is a lot you can do with just relationships vs. projects/permission.

Create a plan for how you can use the influence your team *already has* to make changes, whether it is organizing experiments, researching and recommending tools, or lobbying other functions for more customer facetime.

Avoid directing your own frustration downward. Don't be dishonest, but be cognizant of not compounding their frustration. The attitude down should be hopeful, humorous, supportive, accepting. Take complaints to the person who has more power to do something about it (your boss).

Listen every time. It will get repetitive, but your job is to listen. Underneath the venting, there are usually actual, immediate, urgent problems. Often you can make a lot of positive change by helping unblock the specific situational shit that plagues and discourages the PM.

Reframe fatalist language as compassionate and actionable. It doesn't take much to turn "it's like this everywhere, there's nothing we can do" into "this is very common, so you're not alone. Let's see if we can get advice from others who have dealt with this."

I'll leave it with one of my favorite tactics for tough moments: fantasize. If you could do anything, what would you do? Where would you travel? What kind of art would you make? Would you start a second career as a hairdresser? This reminds you there is an outside & an after.
Be vocal about your opinions and advice when the situation calls for it and learn to accept that people don't have to take them.
Do things you find enriching outside of work so that you never forget that your identity is not wrapped up in how effective you are as a product manager.
Find a good therapist. This is not a joke.

Think about how to expand that sphere. Talk with peers. Learn how other functions work. Invite sales to collaborate with you on sales enablement tools. Work with marketing to understand what metrics they are trying to move. Help ops take tickets. Build trust and rapport.

Work within your sphere of influence and don't get bent out of shape when you can't make change outside that sphere. This is as much for your mental health as anything. Wash your hands of what you can't do anything about.

Reframe "right". Know that the best way to help your org and its customers is to apply good product principles and thinking in a way that honors the context in which you do the work. You'll get more done and make more friends if you flow within your company's constraints.

@DavidMKrell Definitely trying to do more of this type of thinking! Deep empathy for people’s problems is a great organizing principle when you feel otherwise adrift.

And of course, it does not go without saying that I feel very fortunate to come out of 2020 with only an identity crisis under my belt. Lots of folks had economic crises. Lots of folks didn't make it through at all. I am grateful.
2020 has helped me realize is that at this point, I'm not willing to say that this is what I want to do with the rest of my life.
I.e. maybe if I just became a project manager in title, as well as in spirit, I would be more at peace. Or maybe I could do something creative. I love design. I don't know.

I'm starting to look at alternate paths because if I'm going to experience all of these problems no matter where I go, as I suspect is the case, I am not willing to continue to blame myself for not being able to fix them.
I fell in love with a job that now I'm not sure even exists.
This quandary contributed to my COVID-exacerbated stress flame-out earlier this year. Not having the tools or autonomy to do product right, the only advice is to find a new job.
The companies who are often cited as 'doing product right' are places that, ethically, I wouldn't feel good about working. Google. Facebook. Amazon.
(My company is great, by the way, and constantly trying to be better. This thread is about the role of product as I hear it from talking to many, many people).

Product managers mostly cannot escape becoming order-takers. I began to devour 'thought leadership' in the hope of becoming a change agent so that I can leave behind a company more empowered to become product-led. But there is only so much you can do.
I'm reading Cagan's newest book and, as I usually feel when reading product texts, I am not hopeful but frustrated, angry even.
I am starting to question whether the role of 'product manager' even really exists in more than a theoretical way.

Even if he had done anything wrong that night or otherwise not conformed to our problematic 'upstanding citizen' archetype, he had worth. So does everyone who dies at the hands of police.
Wearing a ski mask while Black should not be a death sentence, but don't lose sight of the fact that even *committing a crime* should not be a death sentence.

-- because the fact that he didn't deserve to die would still be true even if there was not such a resounding narrative about what a beautiful person he was. His friends don't need to testify to his good qualities for him to have worth.
My community (and the world) is truly worse off for having Elijah stolen from us. And as much as we need to know these details about who he was, in a way, they are also not relevant--
It seems he routinely told people they were beautiful. The record of his last words circulating that he told the police that they were beautiful and that he loved them.

We can see this reflected in the widespread image of Elijah playing the violin to shelter animals, something he did often on his lunch breaks. He literally could not stop healing others even to briefly rest.

it also serves as a glimpse of what we've lost.  His child-like sense of joy, calling to help and heal, and appreciation for living things shine through in just a few anecdotes from people who loved him.

In this article, his family and friends describe him as exceedingly gentle, generous, and spiritual. Its purpose is to underscore their disbelief that anything about his murder could be justified, but...

@LastMrVivs Agreed; it's not perfect. I asked myself whether a person might like the opportunity to provide that information about their identity even though it itself is not a gender. Use case is non-medical; it's a customer survey for a local business.
Whenever I fill out a form I pay attention to how this simple field is phrased because it seems to speak volumes. How else do you think this could be improved? 7/7

Setting aside the deeper connotations of the 'Other:
 field, I do think there is value in allowing folks to share a gender identity that is not listed here. Especially when the alternative is usually that they are erased completely. 6/7

I think what might make it even better is if these were checkboxes (vs. radio buttons) and allowed multiple selection. The data would be able to show representation of trans women vs. trans men if those people desired to share that information. 5/7

The phrasing of the question is very important: "Gender identity with which you most identify". This gives trans people the freedom to choose either trans or their preferred gender identity of male/female if they wish. 4/7
If you don't fit the binary, your option is 'prefer not to answer'. But I imagine many non-binary people would love to answer truthfully if given the chance. 3/7
Many forms now simply say 'State your gender. Male/female/prefer not to answer.' This upholds an outdated idea that gender is binary. 2/7
